About this opportunity

This project will be hosted by Ericsson Research in Kista. The hosting group in Ericsson Research has a wide competence in fronthaul and indoor radio solutions, 5G and beyond radio system architecture and protocols, and AI/ML techniques for cellular networks.

Thesis description

To provide a good connectivity experience to users, mobile network deployments are dimensioned with respect to peak traffic demands. However, this extreme capacity is not needed all the time since traffic varies throughout the day and time of the year. Moreover, new mobile technologies like 5G or the future 6G, which can provide huge data volumes and throughput, and the increasing number of connected devices to mobile networks exacerbate this difference in resource utilization between times of high and low traffic demand. From both an economic and an environmental point of view, it is preferable to shut down equipment that is not being used to reduce energy consumption at times of low traffic. However, if the resources are removed too soon or are not available when the traffic demand increases, then the user experience will suffer. Therefore, there is a delicate balance that needs to be achieved between energy savings and user satisfaction.

As a leader in wireless communications research and development, Ericsson is constantly exploring new approaches that fully utilize the potential of Artificial Intelligence (AI) to reduce the network energy consumption. The challenge of continuing to provide best-in-class solutions for 5G and beyond radio networks will require handling many diverse deployment scenarios, from dense urban areas to sparsely populated rural areas. The goal of this thesis work is to explore the available reinforcement learning (RL) schemes and identify those that could be suitable for improving the network energy efficiency. For example, an RL agent could decide to turn off/on certain cells based on the current traffic situation and user mobility. The experiments will be carried out in an in-house system-level simulation platform and will preferably be distributed over a computation cloud / cluster for efficiency.

You will be required to:

Study relevant technical specifications and academic literature related to network energy saving and user satisfaction;
Implement and integrate functions and algorithms in the in-house system-level simulator;
Evaluate impacts of different RL policies on the user performance and network energy consumption;
Document the results as a thesis, preferably using LaTeX.
Qualification
We are looking for a student following a master’s program in telecommunication, wireless communication, information and communication technology, engineering physics, or equivalent. The successful candidate must have:

Good understanding of wireless communication systems and techniques;

Knowledge of machine learning in general and reinforcement learning in particular;
Familiarity with machine learning tools such as k-NN, SVMs, neural networks, or random forests, etc., is a plus;
Excellent programming skills in more than one general purpose or scripting language (e.g., Python, Java, C/C++);
Excellent communications skills;

Why join Ericsson?
At Ericsson, you´ll have an outstanding opportunity. The chance to use your skills and imagination to push the boundaries of what´s possible. To build never seen before solutions to some of the world’s toughest problems. You´ll be challenged, but you won’t be alone. You´ll be joining a team of diverse innovators, all driven to go beyond the status quo to craft what comes next.

